1. Financial entities shall establish governance and control frameworks ensuring effective ICT risk management to achieve a high level of digital operational resilience.

2. The management body shall define, approve, oversee and be responsible for implementing ICT risk management arrangements. In doing so, they shall:

(a) bear ultimate responsibility for managing ICT risk;
(b) establish policies ensuring high standards of availability, authenticity, integrity and confidentiality of data;
(c) set clear roles and responsibilities for ICT functions with effective governance arrangements;
(d) set and approve the digital operational resilience strategy, including ICT risk tolerance levels;
(e) approve and review ICT business continuity policy and response and recovery plans;
(f) approve and review ICT internal audit plans and material modifications;
(g) allocate appropriate budgets for digital resilience needs, including security awareness and staff training;
(h) approve and review policy on ICT third-party service provider arrangements;
(i) establish reporting channels regarding: third-party arrangements, planned material changes, impact assessments, and ICT incidents.

3. Non-microenterprises must establish a dedicated role or designate senior management to monitor third-party ICT service provider arrangements.

4. Management body members must actively keep up to date with sufficient knowledge and skills regarding ICT risk through regular training.

1. Financial entities must continuously monitor and control the security and functioning of ICT systems and minimize ICT risk impact through appropriate security tools and procedures.

2. Entities shall design, procure and implement ICT security policies, procedures, protocols and tools ensuring resilience, continuity, and availability of ICT systems, maintaining high standards for data availability, authenticity, integrity, and confidentiality.

3. ICT solutions must:
(a) ensure the security of the means of transfer of data;
(b) minimize corruption, loss, unauthorized access, and technical flaws;
(c) prevent the lack of availability, the impairment of the authenticity and integrity;
(d) protect data from management risks and human error.

4. As part of ICT risk management, entities shall:
(a) develop and document an information security policy;
(b) establish network management using appropriate techniques and automated isolation mechanisms;
(c) implement access limitation policies addressing access rights and ensure a sound administration thereof;
(d) implement strong authentication and cryptographic keys whereby data is encrypted based on approved cryptographic standards;
(e) implement documented ICT change management policies including software and firmware changes;
(f) maintain appropriate and comprehensive documented policies for patches and updates.

Network infrastructure must be instantaneously severed or segmented to minimise contagion in the event of a cyber attack. Change management requires appropriate management approval and specific protocols.

1. Financial entities shall define, establish and implement an ICT-related incident management process to detect, manage and notify ICT-related incidents.

2. Entities must document all ICT incidents and cyber threats, establishing procedures for integrated monitoring, handling, and follow-up to identify root causes and prevent recurrence.

3. The management process requires:

(a) put in place early warning indicators;
(b) procedures to identify, track, log, categorise and classify incidents by priority, severity, and service criticality per Article 18(1);
(c) assign roles and responsibilities that need to be activated for different ICT-related incident types and scenarios;
(d) communication plans for staff, stakeholders, media pursuant to Article 14, client notification, escalation procedures, and information sharing with counterparty entities;
(e) reporting major incidents to senior management and the management body, detailing impact, response, and additional controls;
(f) establish ICT-related incident response procedures to mitigate impacts and ensure that services become operational and secure in a timely manner.

1. Financial entities shall manage ICT third-party risk as an integral component of ICT risk within their ICT risk management framework, in accordance with the following principles:

(a) financial entities that have in place contractual arrangements for the use of ICT services to run their business operations shall, at all times, remain fully responsible for compliance with, and the discharge of, all obligations under this Regulation and applicable financial services law;
(b) financial entities' management of ICT third-party risk shall be implemented in light of the principle of proportionality, taking into account:
(i) the nature, scale, complexity and importance of ICT-related dependencies;
(ii) the risks arising from contractual arrangements on the use of ICT services.

2. Entities shall adopt and regularly review a strategy on ICT third-party risk including policies on use of ICT services supporting critical or important functions, applied individually and on sub-consolidated and consolidated bases.

3. Financial entities shall maintain and update at entity level, and at sub-consolidated and consolidated levels, a register of information in relation to all contractual arrangements on the use of ICT services provided by ICT third-party service providers. The register shall be reported yearly to competent authorities.

4. Before entering into a contractual arrangement on the use of ICT services, financial entities shall:
(a) assess whether the contractual arrangement covers the use of ICT services supporting a critical or important function;
(b) assess whether supervisory conditions for contracting are met;
(c) identify and assess all relevant risks in relation to the contractual arrangement, including concentration risk;
(d) undertake all due diligence on prospective ICT third-party service providers;
(e) identify and assess conflicts of interest that the contractual arrangement may cause.

5. ICT third-party service providers shall comply with appropriate information security standards. Where contractual arrangements concern critical or important functions, financial entities shall, before concluding the arrangements, duly consider the use of the most up-to-date and highest quality information security standards.

6. In exercising access and audit rights on ICT third-party service providers, financial entities shall determine the frequency of audits and inspections based on a risk-based approach and commonly accepted audit standards.

7. Financial entities shall have the right to terminate contractual arrangements where:
(a) significant breach of applicable laws, regulations or contractual terms;
(b) circumstances altering the performance of the functions under the contractual arrangement;
(c) evidence of weaknesses in the ICT third-party service provider's overall ICT risk management;
(d) circumstances where the competent authority can no longer effectively supervise the financial entity.

8. For critical or important functions, financial entities shall put in place exit strategies for orderly termination of the contractual arrangement.

1. The rights and obligations of the financial entity and of the ICT third-party service provider shall be clearly allocated and set out in writing. The full contract shall include the service level agreement and be documented in one written document that is available to the parties on paper, or in a document with another downloadable, durable and accessible format.

2. Contractual arrangements on the use of ICT services shall include at least the following elements:

(a) a clear and complete description of all functions and ICT services to be provided by the ICT third-party service provider, indicating whether subcontracting of an ICT service supporting a critical or important function, or material parts thereof, is permitted, and, where it is, the conditions applicable to such subcontracting;
(b) the locations, namely the regions or countries, where the contracted or subcontracted functions and ICT services are to be provided and where data is to be processed, including the storage location, and the requirement for the ICT third-party service provider to notify the financial entity if it envisages changing such locations;
(c) provisions on availability, authenticity, integrity and confidentiality in relation to the protection of data, including personal data;
(d) provisions on ensuring access to, recovery and return of, in an easily accessible format, personal and non-personal data processed by the ICT third-party service provider in the event of the insolvency, resolution or discontinuation of the business operations of that provider, or in the event of the termination of the contractual arrangements;
(e) service level descriptions, including updates and revisions thereof;
(f) the obligation of the ICT third-party service provider to provide assistance to the financial entity at no additional cost, or at a cost that is determined ex-ante, when an ICT incident that is related to the ICT service provided to the financial entity occurs;
(g) the obligation of the ICT third-party service provider to fully cooperate with the competent authorities and the resolution authorities of the financial entity, including persons appointed by them;
(h) termination rights and related minimum notice periods for the termination of the contractual arrangements, in accordance with the expectations of competent authorities and resolution authorities;
(i) conditions for the participation of ICT third-party service providers in the financial entities' ICT security awareness programmes and digital operational resilience training.

3. For contractual arrangements on the use of ICT services supporting critical or important functions, the following elements shall additionally be included:

(a) full service level descriptions, including updates and revisions thereof, with precise quantitative and qualitative performance targets within the agreed service levels;
(b) notice periods and reporting obligations of the ICT third-party service provider to the financial entity, including notification of any development that might have a material impact on the ICT third-party service provider's ability to effectively provide the ICT services;
(c) requirements for the ICT third-party service provider to implement and test business contingency plans;
(d) the obligation of the ICT third-party service provider to participate in and fully cooperate with the financial entity's TLPT as referred to in Articles 26 and 27;
(e) the right to monitor, on an ongoing basis, the ICT third-party service provider's performance, which shall entail:
(i) unrestricted rights of access, inspection and audit by the financial entity, or an appointed third party, and by the competent authority;
(ii) the right to agree on alternative assurance levels if other clients' rights are affected;
(f) exit strategies, in particular the establishment of a mandatory adequate transition period:
(i) during which the ICT third-party service provider will continue providing the respective functions or ICT services with a view to reducing the risk of disruption at the financial entity or to allowing the financial entity to effectively transition to another third-party service provider or to in-house solutions;
(ii) allowing the financial entity to migrate to another ICT third-party service provider or to in-house solutions.

4. Financial entities and ICT third-party service providers shall use standard contractual clauses developed by public authorities for specific services.

5. The ESAs shall develop draft regulatory technical standards on standard contractual clauses by 17 July 2024.
